.SH USAGE
.
@PACKAGE_NAME@ has been written for \fBconsole mode\fR. If you want to run
@PACKAGE_NAME@ from a terminal in X, you will probably get the best results
if you set \fITERM=linux\fR and use a Linux console terminal.  Both KDE and
GNOME terminals have a facility to start a Linux console in an X terminal
as does Xfce.
.P
By default, Xterm will give unreadable colours.  You will have to set
different colours in the logcfg.dat file.  Also F1 does not work in Xterm,
which is not compatible with Linux consoles.  Other keys (sometimes F4 and
F5) may not work in your Xterm, YMMV.
.P
There are excellent results with the latest KDE, GNOME, and Xfce consoles
(I prefer vi colours).  As @PACKAGE_NAME@ uses ncurses to format its
display you must use a proper font.  (The Linux font works o.k.,
Inconsolata does as well).  If you have problems, try the linux text
console first and work from there.
.P
Normally you start or restart @PACKAGE_NAME@ in fast mode with
\fB@PACKAGE@\fR.  During debugging of a logcfg.dat file you can start in
verbose mode, to have a look at the startup messages.  From @PACKAGE_NAME@
version 0.9.3 you can load different config files with:
.
.IP
.EX
@PACKAGE@ \-f config_file
.EE
.
.P
If you have the packet cluster enabled you will first see the packet
screen.  Log in with your callsign and switch to @PACKAGE_NAME@ with
\fB:\fR<Enter>.  You can come back to the packet screen later with the same
command from the call input field.
.P
You can exit and close @PACKAGE_NAME@ with the \fB:EXIt\fR or \fB:QUIT\fR
commands or with \fBCtrl-C\fR, \fBAlt-Q\fR or \fBAlt-X\fR.
.P
At restart @PACKAGE_NAME@ recalculates the score, which may take some time
depending on the number of QSOs in the logfile and the speed of your
system.  @PACKAGE_NAME@ takes the points as they are in the log, and
calculates the multiplier from either callsign or exchange field (depending
on the contest).
.
.SH COMMANDS
.
These commands are entered in the
.B callsign
field of the main logging screen.  Each command consists of the leading
\(lq\fB:\fR\(rq and at minimum the upper case characters of the command name plus
any needed parameters separated by <Space>.
.
.TP
.B :ADIf
Writes the log to an Amateur Data Interchange Format (ADIF) file (*.adif).
.
.TP
.B :CHAr
Input the number of characters for CW auto-start or 'm' for manual start.
Possible values are: '0' (off), '2'...'5' or 'm' (manual).  
After typing as many characters in the input field or after pressing 
the enter key in manual mode @PACKAGE_NAME@ starts sending 
the callsign without further
keystrokes.  You can type in the rest of the call (but quickly).  As soon
as the sending catches your last typed character @PACKAGE_NAME@
automatically sends the exchange and the cursor jumps to the exchange
field.  <Esc> stops sending.  This works only in CW contests in RUN mode.
.
.TP
.B :CHEck
.TQ
.B :NOCheck
Turn the dupe check window On|Off.
.
.TP
.B :CQDelay
Change CQDelay (in 1/2 seconds, with Up/Down arrows).
.
.TP
.B :CLOff
No cluster information (non-assisted contest operation).
.
.TP
.B :CLUster
.TQ
.B :MAP
Show cluster window or bandmap.
.
.TP
.B :CONtest
Toggle contest mode On/Off.
.
.TP
.B :CTY
.TQ
.B :ZONe
.TQ
.B :MULt
Show needed country multipliers, zones, multipliers per continent (depends
on the contest).
.
.TP
.B :CWMode
.TQ
.B :SSBmode
.TQ
.B :DIGimode
Switch TRX to CW|SSB|Digimode mode.
.
.TP
.B :DEBug_tty
Debug routine for rig communication links.
.
.TP
.B :EDIt
Edit the log with your favourite editor (the editor (vi[m]|joe|e3|mcedit)
can be set in logcfg.dat).
.
.TP
.B :EXIt
.TQ
.B :QUIT
Exit @PACKAGE_NAME@ (synonyms to
.BR Ctl-C ,
.BR Ctl-D ,
.BR Alt-Q ,
and
.BR Alt-X ")."
.
.TP
.B :FILter
Filter cluster info (announce, dx-spots, all).
.
.TP
.B :FREq
Show frequency or band/score information of your other stations.
.
.TP
.B :HELp
Show online help (displays
.B help.txt
from working directory or from @prefix@/share if no local one exists).
.
.TP
.B :INFo
Show network status.
.
.TP
.B :MESsage
Edit CW (Morse Code) messages.
.
.TP
.B :MODe
Toggle TRX mode (CW|SSB|DIG).
.
.TP
.B :PACket
Switch to the packet terminal.  Switch back to @PACKAGE_NAME@ with
\(lq\fB:\fR\(rq.
.
.TP
.B :REConnect
Reopens the connection to the DX cluster in case it was disconnected.
.
.TP
.B :REScore
Recalculates the values in the score window (e.g. after deleting or editing
QSOs).
.
.TP
.B :RITclear
Toggle the RIT reset after QSO On/Off.
.
.TP
.B :SET
.TQ
.B :CFG
Edit various parameters in logcfg.dat file and reload it.
.
.TP
.B :SCAn
Enter the SCAN function (return with <Esc>).
.
.TP
.B :SCOre
Toggle the score window On/Off.
.
.TP
.BI :SCVolume\  dd
Adjust the soundcard volume for the sidetone (Up/Down).  Range: 0-99.
.
.TP
.B :SIMulator
Toggle simulator mode.  In simulator mode you can work a complete
CQWW CW contest in TR-Log mode.  Set \fBCONTEST=\fIcqww\fR.
.
.TP
.B :SOUnd
The SOUND recorder is a utility to record the voice keyer messages and
enables you to record the complete contest in chunks of 1 hour to the hard
drive.  It does this in the directory: ~/@PACKAGE@/soundlogs.  The sound
recorder uses a script called
.B soundlog
which has to be located in ~/@PACKAGE@/soundlogs.  It can be found in the
.B scripts
directory.  If your soundcard is different from /dev/dsp you can use the
.B SC_DEVICE
parameter in the logcfg.dat file (my soundcard is at SC_DEVICE=/dev/dsp1).
The file extension is .au, the Sun ulaw format.  The recorder produces < 60
MB per hour.  This means you can record a complete CQWW in less than 3 GB.
If your disk cannot handle this, FTP the soundfile to a server every hour.
.IP
.BR "F1 ... F12" ,\  s ,\  c ,\ ...
will record the voice keyer message for that key.
.IP
.BR 1 :
Start contest recording to ddhhmm.au.
.IP
.BR 2 :
Stop contest recording.
.IP
.BR 3 :
Play back contest recording ddhh[mm][:xx].
.RS
.RS
.P
xx is the offset from the start of the file e.g.:
.P
2110 will start from beginning of the day 21 hr 10:00 file.
.P
21100013:00 will start from day 21, hh 10, mm 00, + 13 minutes: 0 seconds.
.RE
.RE
.IP
To create a new file every hour add a cron job to run the following command
every hour:
.RS
.RS
.P
.EX
/usr/bin/pkill \-f sox > /dev/null 2> /dev/null
.EE
.P
Running the cron job at other intervals will create sound recordings of the
interval period in length.
.RE
.RE
.IP
Once started the recorder will run until the lock file
.B ~/.VRlock
is removed.
.
.TP
.B :SYNc
Synchronize the logfile of this node with the logfile pointed to by
parameter SYNCFILE=<user:password@host/dir/logfile>.  @PACKAGE_NAME@ will
.B wget
the logfile from the relevant node, make a dated backup of your local
logfile, and merge the 2 files.  The score will be recalculated.
.
.TP
.BI :TONe\  [dd]d
Set PC sidetone frequency in Hertz.  Range: 300-900, 0 = Off.
.
.TP
.B :TRXcontrol
Toggle rig control On/Off.  Default is Off (only makes sense with rig control
capability)
.
.TP
.B :VIEw
View the log with
.BR less (1).
.
.TP
.B :WRIte
Write cabrillo file according to specified format (see
.B CABRILLO=
statement).
.
.SH KEYS
.
The keymap refers to the Linux text console.  It may be slightly different
on X terminals.  Turn off any key recognition by the terminal for its own
purposes (menu access, help display, etc.).  Pay special attention to the
F1-F12 and Alt-<char> keys.  Moreover on some systems you must set
\fB\TERM=linux\fR\ or \fB\TERM=rxvt\fR.  This also works under VNC.
.
.TP
.B PgUp
Increase CW (Morse Code) speed (from call and exchange fields).
.IP
If field not empty and CHANGE_RST is set: change RST value.
.
.TP
.B PgDown
Decrease CW (Morse Code) speed (from call and exchange fields).
.IP
If field not empty and CHANGE_RST is set: change RST value.
.
.TP
.B Ctrl-PgUp
Increase Auto_CQ delay (+1/2 sec).
.IP
Set Auto_CW delay to message length + pause length.  This is because
@PACKAGE_NAME@ does not know when the cwdaemon is ready.
.
.TP
.B Ctrl-PgDown
Decrease Auto_CQ delay (\-1/2 sec).
.
.TP
.B F1-F11
Send CW, RTTY or VOICE message.
.
.TP
.B F12
Start Auto_CQ (sends F12 message).
.
.TP
.B Tab
Switch between call input and exchange fields.
.
.TP
.B Space
Switch from call input to exchange field.
.
.TP
.BR +\  (Plus)
Toggle CQ/S&P mode (TR-Log mode) or send F3 message + log QSO (CT mode).
.
.TP
.BR \(<-\  (Left-Arrow)
Change band if callsign field empty (enter edit mode if callsign present,
leave edit mode with <Enter> or <Esc>).
.
.TP
.BR \(->\  (Right-Arrow)
Change band.
.
.TP
.B Enter
Smart key for contest mode: Calls CQ, Calls station, Sends exchange, Logs
the QSO.
.
.TP
.BR \(rs\  (Backslash)
Log QSO without CW output.
.
.TP
.BR ;\  (Semicolon)
Insert note in log.
.
.TP
.BR ,\  (comma)
Keyboard on.  This works only when the call input field is empty; use Ctrl-K if it is not.
.
.TP
.B Escape
Return to call input field, keyboard off, stop CW, reset call and exchange (universal undo).
.
.TP
.BR \(dq\  "(Double quotation)"
Send talk message to other @PACKAGE_NAME@ nodes.
.
.TP
.BR \-\  (Minus)
Delete last QSO (Use :REScore to correct scoring afterward).
.
.TP
.BR \[ua]\  (Up-Arrow)
Edit last QSO: Insert, overwrite, and delete; + log view.
.
.TP
.BR =\  (Equals)
Confirm last call.
.
.TP
.BR _\  (Underscore)
Confirm last exchange.
.
.TP
.BR {\  "(Open brace)"
In RTTY (DIGIMODE), keyboard mode switch TX on.
.
.TP
.BR }\  "(Close brace)"
In RTTY (DIGIMODE), keyboard mode switch TX off (RX).
.
.TP
.BR \e\  (Backslash)
In RTTY (DIGIMODE), keyboard mode switch controller to command mode
(back to operating mode with \(aqK <Enter>\(aq.
.
.TP
.BR #\  (Hash)
Transceiver VFO frequency \(-> mem, mem \(-> transceiver VFO frequency.
.
.TP
.BR !\  (Exclamation)
Get a new shell.  Come back with \(aqexit\(aq.
.
.TP
.BR .\  (Period)
Change bandmap filter configuration.  You can filter to show spots from all
or own band only, from all/own mode only and if you want to see dupes or
not (see the help display).
.
.TP
.B Ctrl-A
Add a spot to bandmap and broadcast it on the local network.
.
.TP
.B Ctrl-B
Send a spot to the DX Cluster.
.
.TP
.B Ctrl-C
.TQ
